{"title_page": "The Marvel Super Heroes", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name    = The Marvel Super Heroes\n| image        = Marvel-super-heroes-ad.jpg\n| caption      = Print advertisement for the show\n| genre        = {{plainlist|\n*[[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n*[[Action fiction|Action]]\n*[[Adventure fiction|Adventure]]}}\n| based_on = {{based on|[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]||[[Stan Lee]]|[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n| opentheme = \"The Marvel Super Heroes Has Arrived!\"\n| endtheme = \"The Merry Marvel Marching Society\"\n| runtime      = 30 min\n| starring     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peg Dixon]]\n* [[Paul Soles]]\n* Sandy Becker\n* [[John Vernon]]\n* [[Jack Creley]]\n}}\n| country      = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n}}\n| company      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Grantray-Lawrence Animation]]\n* [[Marvel Comics|Marvel Comics Group]]\n}}\n| distributor  = [[Krantz Films]]<!-- Only add the original distributor of the show if the show has one, as Infobox Television says \" The names of the original distribution company or companies.\" If the show doesn't have a distributor, leave it blank. -->\n| network      = [[Broadcast syndication|First-run syndication]]\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|1966|9|1}}\n| last_aired   = {{End date|1966|12|1}}\n| num_episodes = 65 (195 segments)\n| website      = \n}}\n'''''The Marvel Super Heroes'''''<ref>Title per {{cite video | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLJZyIXu2hA | title = The Marvel Super Heroes | publisher = (Animated opening credits) YouTube | accessdate = 2013-10-25 | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/6KeFEUV0U?url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLJZyIXu2hA | archivedate = October 26, 2013 | url-status = live }} NOTE: The title is rendered inaccurately as \"The Marvel Superheroes\" at [http://imdb.com/title/tt0122826/ its entry] on [[IMDb]] and at [http://www.tv.com/the-marvel-superheroes/show/29637/summary.html TV.com].</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[animated television series]] starring five [[comic book]] [[superhero]]es from [[Marvel Comics]]. The first TV series based on Marvel characters, it debuted in [[broadcast syndication|syndication]] on [[United States|U.S.]] television in 1966.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=379}}</ref>\n\nProduced by [[Grantray-Lawrence Animation]], headed by Grant Simmons, Ray Patterson and Robert Lawrence,<ref>Robert Lawrence interview, ''[[Jack Kirby Collector]]'' #41, Fall 2004, pp. 42-47.</ref> it was an umbrella series of five segments, each approximately seven minutes long, broadcast on local [[television stations]] that aired the show at different times. <!--note: few were actually independent stations, as some have written; most were network affiliates, as can be clicked through and seen in the list that appears below in this article--> The series ran initially as a half-hour program made up of three seven-minute segments of a single superhero, separated by a short description of one of the other four heroes. It has also been broadcast as a mixture of various heroes in a half-hour timeslot, and as individual segments as filler or within a [[children's TV program]].<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981, Part 1: Animated Cartoon Series |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/176/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=177-179}}</ref>\n\nThe segments were: \"[[Captain America]]\", \"[[Hulk|The Incredible Hulk]]\", \"[[Iron Man]]\", \"[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|The Mighty Thor]]\" (1962), and \"[[Namor|The Sub-Mariner]]\".\n\n==Production==\nSixty-five half-hour episodes of three seven-minute chapters were produced, for a total of 195 segments that ran initially in broadcast syndication from September 1, 1966 to December 1, 1966.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.tv.com/the-marvel-superheroes/show/29637/episode_listings.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=tabssh&tag=tabs;episodes |title='&#39;The Marvel Superheroes'&#39; Episode Guide |publisher=[[TV.com]] |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last = Thomas|first = Roy|authorlink = Roy Thomas|author2=Sanderson, Peter |authorlink2=Peter Sanderson |title = The Marvel Vault: A Museum-in-a-Book with Rare Collectibles from the World of Marvel|publisher = [[Running Press]]|year = 2007|page = 101|isbn = 978-0762428441|quote= In 1966, television production company Grantray-Lawrence produced a series of five half-hour semi-animated shows under the banner title ''Marvel Superheroes''.<!-- spelling as in cited source --> ''Captain America'' (original comics appearance in 1941), ''The Incredible Hulk'' (1962), ''Iron Man'' (1963), ''The Mighty Thor'', and ''Sub-Mariner'' (1939) all made their television debuts.}}</ref>\n\nThe series, produced in color, had extremely [[limited animation]] produced by [[xerography]], consisting of photocopied images taken directly from the comics and manipulated to minimize the need for animation production. The cartoons were presented as a series of static comic-strip panel images; generally the only movement involved the lips when a character spoke, the eyes, and the occasional arm or leg, or a fully animated black silhouette. The series used the original stories largely in their entirety, showcasing [[Jack Kirby]], [[Steve Ditko]] and [[Don Heck]] art, among others, from the period fans and historians call the [[Silver Age of comic books]].\n\n[[Stan Lee]], Marvel's editor and art director at the time, said in 2004 that he believed publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]] negotiated the deal with Grantray-Lawrence and that Lawrence chose the characters to be used. Lawrence rented Lee and his wife a [[penthouse apartment]] at 30 East 60th Street, near [[Madison Avenue]], for Lee's use while he worked on the series. (Lee lived in [[Hewlett Harbor, New York|Hewlett Harbor]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on [[Long Island]], at the time.) Lee recalled, \"I really don't remember any reaction from the Marvel artists involved. I wish I could claim to have written the [theme song] lyrics, because I think they're brilliant, but alas, I didn't\".<ref>{{Cite journal|title=A Minute of Stan's Time|publisher= (sidebar, Jack Kirby Collector |issue=41 |date=Fall 2004|page= 47|first=Adam |last=McGovern}}</ref> The songs were written by [[Jacques Urbont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmusicsociety.org/news_events/features/2015/071415.html?isArchive=071415|title=The Marvel Super Heroes Songs: The Inside Story|publisher=The Film Music Society|author=Jon Burlingame|date=2015-07-14|accessdate=2018-11-18}}</ref> In the meantime, Grantray-Lawrence subcontracted production of ''The Mighty Thor'' segments to [[Famous Studios|Paramount Cartoon Studios]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} (the animation division of [[Paramount Pictures]], formerly known as Famous Studios), headed at that time by [[Fleischer Studios]] veteran [[Shamus Culhane]].\n\nMarvel announced the series in the \"Marvel Bullpen Bulletins\" of the November 1966 issues, stating in that monthly fan page's hyperbolic style that, \"It won't be long before our swingin' super-heroes <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[sic]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> make their star-studded debut on TV, appearing five nights a week &mdash; that's right, five &mdash; count 'em &mdash; five nights a week, for a half-hour each night. So you've just got time to make sure your set's in good working order &mdash; check your local paper for time and station &mdash; and prepare to have a ball!\"<ref>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins: \"Sensational Secrets and Incredible Inside Information Guilelessly Guaranteed to Avail You Naught!\", in ''[[Tales of Suspense]]'' #83 (Nov. 1966) and other Marvel comics that month.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{expand list|date=November 2014}}\n* [[Carl Banas]] - [[Bucky Barnes]], [[Super-Adaptoid]] \n* [[Sandy Becker]] - [[Captain America|Steve Rogers / Captain America]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tvparty.com/lostny2marvel.html | title= New York City Kid Show Roundup: Marvel Superheroes [sic] | first=Kevin S. |last= Butler | date= n.d. | publisher=TVParty.com | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20010904184549/http://www.tvparty.com/lostny2marvel.html | archivedate= September 4, 2001|url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[Bernard Cowan]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Narrator, [[Odin (character)|Odin]], [[Melter]], Captain Torak, Morgan, [[Ringmaster (comics)|Ringmaster]], Sando/Colonel Von Kraz, \n* [[Jack Creley]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Jack Frost/Professor Shapanka\n* [[Len Carlson]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], [[Loki (comics)|Loki]], [[Mad Thinker]], [[Black Knight (Nathan Garrett)|Nathan Garrett / Black Knight]], President\n* Vern Chapman - [[Edwin Jarvis]], [[Super-Adaptoid]]\n* Henry Comor - [[Gargantus]]\n* Gillie Fenwick - [[Heinrich Zemo|Baron Heinrich Zemo]], [[Radioactive Man (comics)|Radioactive Man]], [[Leader (comics)|Leader]], [[Batroc the Leaper]], [[Space Phantom]], Dr. Cedric Rawlings, [[Heimdall (comics)|Heimdall]], [[Mister Hyde (comics)|Mister Hyde]], Sandu, Premiere Pouldu\n* [[Max Ferguson]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Hulk]]<ref>''Weekend Magazine'' (May 24, 1969)</ref>\n* [[Margaret Griffin]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> - [[Pepper Potts]], [[Black Widow (Natasha Romanova)|Black Widow]], Countess de la Spirosa\n* [[Tom Harvey]] - [[Happy Hogan (comics)|Happy Hogan]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Hank Pym|Giant-Man]], [[Iceman (Marvel Comics)|Iceman]], [[Chameleon (Marvel Comics)|Chameleon]], [[Super-Skrull]], [[Crimson Dynamo|Anton Vanko / Crimson Dynamo]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> Borok\n* [[Paul Kligman]] - [[Thunderbolt Ross]], [[Red Skull]], [[Krang (Marvel Comics)|Warlord Krang]], [[Mole Man]], [[Metal Master (comics)|Metal Master]], [[Erik Josten|Power Man]]\n* Vita Linder<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Betty Ross]], [[Dorma (comics)|Lady Dorma]], [[Jane Foster (comics)|Jane Foster]], [[Enchantress (Marvel Comics)|Enchantress]], [[Scarlet Witch]],  [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]], [[Sharon Carter]], [[Peggy Carter]], [[Lorelei (Asgardian)|Lorelei]], Celia Rawlings, Hippolyta\n* [[Don Mason (actor)|Don Mason]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref>\n* Douglas Master - Senator Harrington Boyd<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n* [[Ed McNamara]] - [[Swordsman (comics)|Swordsman]], [[Titanium Man]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Boomerang (comics)|Boomerang]], [[Mad Thinker]]\n* Claude Rae<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref>\n* Henry Ramer<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Major Uberhart, [[Doctor Doom]], Wolfgang, Vashti, [[Mandarin (comics)|Mandarin]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n* [[Paul Soles]] - [[Hulk|Bruce Banner]], [[Attuma]], [[Rick Jones (comics)|Rick Jones]]\n* [[John Vernon]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Iron Man|Iron Man/Tony Stark]],<ref>http://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/iron-man-the-first-and-cheapest</ref> [[Namor|Sub-Mariner/Prince Namor]],<ref>http://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/iron-man-the-first-and-cheapest</ref> Major [[Glenn Talbot]], Major Corey\n* [[Chris Wiggins]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor/Dr. Donald Blake]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chriswigginsonline.8k.com/films.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224021156/http://chriswigginsonline.8k.com/films.html |archivedate=2015-02-24 }}</ref> [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Kraven the Hunter|Kraven]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Grey Gargoyle]], Byrrah, [[Balder (comics)|Balder]], [[Blizzard (comics)|Jack Frost]], Molto, [[Professor X]], [[Count Nefaria]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n\nFor [[WNAC-TV]] in Boston, Arthur Pierce portrayed Captain America in live-action segments for the show. Actors portraying other characters, including Dr. Doom, Hulk, and Bucky, also appeared in live-action segments. The segments were scripted by Superman co-creator [[Jerry Siegel]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Age of TV Heroes: The Live-Action Adventures of Your Favorite Comic Book Characters |last=Hofius |first=Jason |authorlink= |author2=George Khoury   | year = 2010 | publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |location= |isbn=1-60549-010-5}}</ref>\n\n==Guest characters==\nAppearing in guest roles were:\n* [[X-Men|The X-Men]] &mdash; The original lineup of the [[Warren Worthington|Angel]], the [[Beast (comics)|Beast]], [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]], [[Iceman (comics)|Iceman]], and [[Jean Grey|Marvel Girl]] appeared in a Sub-Mariner episode, \"Dr. Doom's Day / The Doomed Allegiance / Tug of Death\". The story was an adaptation of ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #6 (Sept. 1962), but since Grantray-Lawrence Animation did not own rights to the [[Fantastic Four (1967 animated series)|Fantastic Four]], the producers substituted the X-Men &mdash; although referring to them instead as \"Allies for Peace\". However, the characters retained their original designs and individual names from the comics.\n* [[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]] &mdash; Episode 8 of The Incredible Hulk was an adaptation of ''Avengers'' #2 (Nov. 1963), and co-starred Thor, Iron Man (with his early golden armor recolored to match the red-and-gold design featured in the Iron Man episodes), [[Giant-Man]], the [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]]. The lineup beginning in ''Avengers'' #4 (March 1964), with Thor, Iron Man, Giant-Man, the Wasp and the newly installed Captain America, appears in several ''Captain America'' episodes, as does the later line-up from Avengers #16 with [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]], [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], and the [[Scarlet Witch]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2010}}\nEach episode consisted of three chapters.\n\n===''Captain America''===\n[[File:MSH-CaptainAmerica 1966TVtoon.jpg|thumb|250px|A [[Captain America]] title card]]\n*Episode 1: The Origin of [[Captain America]], Wreckers Among Us, Enter [[Red Skull]]\n*Episode 2: The Sentinel and the Spy, The Fantastic Origin of the Red Skull, Lest Tyranny Triumph\n*Episode 3: Midnight in Greymoor Castle, If This Be Treason, When You Lie Down With Dogs\n*Episode 4: Return of Captain America, The Search, To Live Again\n*Episode 5: [[Baron Zemo|Zemo]] and the [[Masters of Evil]], Zemo Strikes, The Fury of Zemo\n*Episode 6: The Revenge of Captain America, The Trap Is Sprung, So Dies A Villain\n*Episode 7: Let The Past Be Gone, The [[Super-Adaptoid|Adaptoid]], The [[Super-Adaptoid|Super Adaptoid]]\n*Episode 8: Coming of the [[Swordsman (comics)#Jacques Duquesne|Swordsman]], Vengeance Is Ours, Emissary of Destruction\n*Episode 9: Bitter Taste of Defeat, Sorcery Triumph, The Road Back\n*Episode 10: Doorway to Doom, When the Commissar Commands, Duel Or Die\n*Episode 11: The [[Sleeper (Marvel Comics)|Sleeper]] Shall Awake, Where Walks the Sleeper, The Final Sleep\n*Episode 12: The Girl from Cap's Past, The Stage Is Set, 30 Minutes to Live\n*Episode 13: The Red Skull Lives, He Who Holds the [[Cosmic Cube]], The Red Skull Supreme\n\n===''The Incredible Hulk''===\n[[File:Hulk Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|250px|One depiction of the [[Hulk]] in ''The Marvel Super Heroes'']]\n*Episode 1: The Origin of the [[Hulk]], Enter the Gorgon, To Be a Man\n*Episode 2: Terror of the Toadmen, Bruce Banner: Wanted For Treason, Hulk Runs Amok\n*Episode 3: A Titan Rides the Train, The Horde of Humanoids, On the Rampage!\n*Episode 4: The Power of Dr. Banner, Where Strides the Behemoth, Back from the Dead\n*Episode 5: Micro Monsters, The Lair of the [[Leader (comics)|Leader]], To Live Again\n*Episode 6: Brawn Against Brain, Captured At Last, Enter the [[Chameleon (comics)|Chameleon]]\n*Episode 7: Within this Monster Dwells a Man; Another World, Another Foe; The Wisdom of the [[Uatu|Watcher]]\n*Episode 8: The [[Space Phantom]], Sting of the Wasp, Exit the Hulk\n*Episode 9: Hulk vs. Metal Master, The Master Tests His Metal, Mind Over Metal\n*Episode 10: The [[Ringmaster (comics)|Ringmaster]], Captive of the [[Circus of Crime|Circus]], The Grand Finale\n*Episode 11: Enter [[Tyrannus (comics)|Tyrannus]], Beauty & The Beast, They Dwell in the Depths\n*Episode 12: Terror of the T-Gun, I Against A World, Bruce Banner is the Hulk\n*Episode 13: The Man Called Boomerang; Hulk Intervenes; Less Than Monster, More Than Man\n\n===''The Invincible Iron Man<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>''===\n[[File:Iron Man Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|250px|One depiction of [[Iron Man]] in the series]]\n*Episode 1: Double Disaster, Enter [[Happy Hogan (comics)|Happy Hogan]], Of Ice and Men\n*Episode 2: The Death of [[Tony Stark]]!, The Hands of the [[Mandarin (comics)|Mandarin]], The Origin of The Mandarin\n*Episode 3: [[Ultimo (Marvel Comics)|Ultimo]], Ultimo Lives, Crescendo\n*Episode 4: The Mandarin's Revenge!, The Mandarin's Death Ray, No One Escapes the Mandarin\n*Episode 5: [[Crimson Dynamo]]!, The Crimson Dynamo Strikes, Captured\n*Episode 6: Enter [[Clint Barton|Hawkeye]], So Spins the Web, Triple Jeopardy\n*Episode 7: If I Die, Let It Be With Honor; Fight On, For A World Is Watching; What Price Victory?\n*Episode 8: The [[Mole Man (comics)|Moleman]] Strikes, The Dragon of the Flames, Decision Under the Earth\n*Episode 9: The Other [[Iron Man]]!, Death Duel, Into The Jaws of the Death\n*Episode 10: The Cliffs of Doom!, The False Captain America, The Unmasking\n*Episode 11: My Life For Yours, The [[Nathan Garrett|Black Knight]]'s Gambit, The Menace of the Monster\n*Episode 12: The Dream Master, If A Man Be Mad, Duel In Space\n*Episode 13: Beauty and the Armor, Peril in Space, As A City Watches\n\n===''The Mighty Thor''===\n[[File:Thor Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] title card]]\n*Episode 1: Trapped by [[Loki (Marvel Comics)|Loki]], The Vengeance of Loki, The Defeat of Loki\n*Episode 2: Chained Evil; Sandu, Master of the Supernatural; Enchanted Hammer\n*Episode 3: [[Enchantress (comics)|Enchantress]] and [[Executioner (comics)|Executioner]], Giants Walk the Earth, Battle of the Gods\n*Episode 4: At the Mercy of Loki, Trial of the Gods, Return To Earth\n*Episode 5: The [[Absorbing Man]]; In My Hands, This Hammer; Vengeance of the Thunder God\n*Episode 6: To Kill A Thunder God, The Day of the [[Destroyer (Thor)|Destroyer]], Terror of the Tomb\n*Episode 7: The [[Grey Gargoyle]], The Wrath of [[Odin (Marvel Comics)|Odin]], Triumph in Stone\n*Episode 8: The Mysterious [[Mister Hyde (comics)|Mister Hyde]], Revenge of Mr. Hyde, [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]'s Showdown with Mr. Hyde\n*Episode 9: Every Hand Against Him, The Power of the Thunder God, The Power of Odin\n*Episode 10: The [[Tomorrow Man]], Return of Zarrko, Slave of Tomorrow Man\n*Episode 11: Enter [[Hercules (Marvel Comics)|Hercules]], When Meet Immortals, Whom the Gods Would Destroy\n*Episode 12: The Power of [[Pluto (Marvel Comics)|Pluto]], The Verdict of [[Zeus (Marvel Comics)|Zeus]], Thunder in the Netherworld\n*Episode 13: [[Subterranea (comics)#Lava Men|Molto]], the Lava Man; Invasion of the Lava Man; Living Rock\n\n===''Prince Namor the Sub-Mariner''===\n[[File:MSH-Submariner 1966TVtoon.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Title card for a [[Sub-Mariner]] episode]]\n*Episode 1: Peril in the Surface World, So Spreads the Net, The Unveiling\n*Episode 2: The Start of the Quest!, Escape to Nowhere, A Prince There Was\n*Episode 3: Not All My Power Can Save Me!, When Fails the Quest, The End of the Quest\n*Episode 4: Atlantis Under Attack, The Sands of Terror, The Iron Idol of Infamy\n*Episode 5: The Thing from Space, No Escape for [[Namor]], A Prince Dies Fighting\n*Episode 6: To Conquer a Crown, A Prince No More, He Who Wears the Crown\n*Episode 7: To Walk Amongst Men!, When Rises the Behemoth, To the Death\n*Episode 8: The World Within!, Atlantis Is Doomed, Quest for X-Atom\n*Episode 9: Beware the Siren Song, Spell of Lorelei, Return of the Mud Beast\n*Episode 10: Ship of Doom, Fall of Atlantis, Forces of Vengeance\n*Episode 11: The Planet of Doom, To Test a Prince, To Save a Planet\n*Episode 12: [[Doctor Doom|Dr. Doom]]'s Day, The Doomed Allegiance, Tug of Death\n*Episode 13: Let the Stranger Die..!, To Destroy a Tyrant, Save A City\n\n==Stations==\n'''Source:''' Marvel Comics house ads in ''[[Strange Tales]]'' #150 (Nov. 1966) and ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' #45 (Feb. 1967), each of which said the list was \"incomplete at time of publication\".\n\n;Alphabetized by city\n*[[WTEN-TV]] / Channel 10 \u2022 [[Albany, New York]]\n*[[WBAL-TV|WBAL]] / Channel 11 \u2022 [[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n*[[WNEM-TV|WNEM]] / Channel 5 \u2022 [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]]/[[Saginaw, Michigan]]\n*[[WHDH-TV|WNAC]] / Channel 7 \u2022 [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n*[[WKBW-TV|WKBW]] / Channel 7 \u2022 [[Buffalo, New York]]\n*WAZ / Channel 3 \u2022 [[Charleston, West Virginia]] (became [[WSAZ-TV|WSAZ]] / Channel 3 \u2022 [[Huntington, West Virginia]])\n*[[WCCB-TV]] / Channel 18\u2022 [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]\n*[[WGN-TV|WGN]] / Channel 9 \u2022 [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n*[[CKLW (AM)#CKLW-FM and CKLW-TV|CKLW]] / Channel 9 \u2022 [[Detroit, Michigan]] (became [[CBET-DT|CBET]] / Channel 9 \u2022 [[Windsor, Ontario]], Canada)\n*[[KWGN-TV]] / Channel 2\u2022 [[Denver, Colorado]]\n*[[KATV]]/ Channel 7\u2022 [[Little Rock, Arkansas]]\n*KHJ (became [[KCAL-TV]]) / Channel 9 \u2022 [[Los Angeles, California]]\n*[[WHBQ-TV|WHBQ]] / Channel 13 \u2022 [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n*[[WVUE-DT|WVUE]] / Channel 12 \u2022 [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n*WOR (became [[WWOR-TV|WWOR]]) / Channel 9 \u2022 [[New York City, New York]]\n*[[KYW-TV|KYW]] / Channel 3 \u2022 [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n*[[WPGH-TV]] / Channel 53 \u2022 [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n*WGAN (now [[WGME-TV|WGME]]) / Channel 13 \u2022 [[Portland, Maine]]\n*WPRO (became [[WPRI-TV|WPRI]]) / Channel 12 \u2022 [[Providence, Rhode Island]]\n*[[WHEC-TV|WHEC]] / Channel 10 \u2022 [[Rochester, New York]]\n*KSD (became [[KSDK]]) / Channel 5 \u2022 [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]\n*KCPX (became [[KTVX]]) / Channel 4 \u2022 [[Salt Lake City, Utah]] (ad erroneously listed station as WCPX)\n*[[WAPA-TV|WAPA]] / Channel 4 \u2022 [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n*WHEN (became [[WTVH]]) / Channel 5 \u2022 [[Syracuse, New York]]\n*[[WTTG]] / Channel 5 \u2022 [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Home media==\n<!--No authoritative confirmation for the following appears to exist on the Web. Wikipedia disallows forum postings or blogs, or commercial sales site.\nSegments of the series were released on [[VHS]] in 1985 from Prism Entertainment as part of the \"Marvel Comics Video Library\" series. In the early 1990s, other segments of the series, as well as some other Marvel Comics based animated series, were re-released on VHS, with distribution by Best Film & Video Corp. under the '''Marvel Video!''' banner from 1991-1994.-->\nSegments of the series appear on at least two [[VHS]] [[home video]] releases, containing three [[videocassettes]] each: ''Marvel Superheroes: Triple Pack #1'' ([[Universal Product Code|UPC]] #024543004127) and ''Marvel's Mightiest Heroes: Triple Pack #2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/marvels_mightiest_heroes_triple_pack_2/ |title='Marvel's Mightiest Heroes: Triple Pack #2' |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|Fox Video]] released a version titled ''Marvel's Mightiest Super Heroes Gift Set'' ([[European Article Number|EAN]] #0024543004134).\n\nIn 2003, Hulk segments giving his [[origin story]] appeared as an extra on the [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] DVD release of the 1996 [[animated television series]] ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1996 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/read.php?ID=6664 |title='The Incredible Hulk' (Animated Series) |first=James W. |last=Powell |publisher=(review) DVDTalk.com |date=June 17, 2003|accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] announced plans to release ''The Marvel Superheroes Show'' on June 28, 2005, as a five-DVD set titled ''The 60's Superheroes''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2176 |title=The Marvel Superheroes - Capt. America! Hulk! Thor! Iron Man! Sub-Mariner! |first=David |last=Lambert |publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com |date=September 24, 2004 |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060208224211/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2176 |archivedate=February 8, 2006 }}</ref> By February 2005, however, the release was off the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2838|title=The Marvel Superheroes - Studio Says 'Superheroes' are Off the Schedule|first=David|last=Lambert|publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com|date=February 1, 2005|accessdate=2011-01-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818030710/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2838|archivedate=August 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2007, the [[United Kingdom|UK]] company Maximum Entertainment released four two-disc sets, for [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 2]], each set containing 13 episodes of the Captain America, Iron Man, Sub-Mariner and Thor segments respectively, with each episode re-edited into continuous, half-hour segments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.toonzone.net/article.php?ID=18200|date=July 23, 2007|title='The Marvel Super Heroes': Classic Comics in Suspended Animation|author=\"Jon T\" (pseudonym)|publisher=Toon Zone|accessdate=2011-01-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211034951/http://news.toonzone.net/article.php?ID=18200|archivedate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> On August 25, 2008, the UK  company Liberation Entertainment released a two-disc set of the Hulk segments, re-edited into 13 20-minute episodes.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Canada|Cartoon|Speculative fiction|1960s}}\n* {{imdb title|206513|The Sub-Mariner}}\n* {{imdb title|0206474|Captain America}}\n* {{imdb title|0206488|The Incredible Hulk}}\n* {{imdb title|0206490|Iron Man}}\n* {{imdb title|0156221|The Mighty Thor}}\n* {{bcdb |Other_Studios/G/Grantray-Lawrence_Animation/The_Marvel_Superheroes_Show/|The Marvel Superheroes Show}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-marvel-superheroes|The Marvel Super Heroes}}\n*Toonarific pages for [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=marvel+superheroes&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2306 ''Captain America''], [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=marvel+superheroes&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2309 ''The Incredible Hulk''], [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=marvel+superheroes&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2307 ''The Invincible Iron Man''], [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=marvel+superheroes&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2310 ''The Mighty Thor''], [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?s_search=marvel+superheroes&Button_Update=Search&show_id=2308 ''Prince Namor The Sub-Mariner'']\n\n===Audio/video===\n*[http://www.toontracker.com/realaudio/ttra60-2.htm The Toon Tracker RealAudio Cartoon Themes from 1966-1969 Page] (audio)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K3g0tzgIezY YouTube clip of the show's intro]\n*YouTube clips of the show's segment intros\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cVU4HURKEXs Captain America]\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b9u7GjNkp5Y The Incredible Hulk]\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LjTIVaSnRR0 Iron Man]\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=80P_MF_XgOY The Mighty Thor]\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tRWeaHkxXwE The Sub-Mariner]\n**[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iJcJbLE6gks The Marvel Super Heroes Theme Songs]\n{{Navboxes\n|title=The Marvel Super Heroes\n|list1=\n{{Captain America}}\n{{Hulk}}\n{{Iron Man}}\n{{Thor}}\n{{Namor}}\n{{Marvel animation}}\n{{Animated television series created for syndication}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marvel Superheroes, The}}\n[[Category:1960s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1966 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1966 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated anthology television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:Captain America in other media]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hulk (comics) television series]]\n[[Category:Iron Man television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series based on Marvel Comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on Marvel Comics]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Thor (Marvel Comics) in other media]]\n[[Category:Scarlet Witch]]\n[[Category:Television series by Grantray-Lawrence Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series by Famous Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name    = The Marvel Super Heroes\n| image        = Marvel-super-heroes-ad.jpg\n| caption      = Print advertisement for the show\n| genre        = {{plainlist|\n*[[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n*[[Action fiction|Action]]\n*[[Adventure fiction|Adventure]]}}\n| based_on = {{based on|[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]||[[Stan Lee]]|[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n| opentheme = \"The Marvel Super Heroes Has Arrived!\"\n| endtheme = \"The Merry Marvel Marching Society\"\n| runtime      = 30 min\n| starring     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peg Dixon]]\n* [[Paul Soles]]\n* Sandy Becker\n* [[John Vernon]]\n* [[Jack Creley]]\n}}\n| country      = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n}}\n| company      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Grantray-Lawrence Animation]]\n* [[Marvel Comics|Marvel Comics Group]]\n}}\n| distributor  = [[Krantz Films]]<!-- Only add the original distributor of the show if the show has one, as Infobox Television says \" The names of the original distribution company or companies.\" If the show doesn't have a distributor, leave it blank. -->\n| network      = [[Broadcast syndication|First-run syndication]]\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|1966|9|1}}\n| last_aired   = {{End date|1966|12|1}}\n| num_episodes = 65\n| website      = \n}}\n'''''The Marvel Super Heroes'''''<ref>Title per {{cite video | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLJZyIXu2hA | title = The Marvel Super Heroes | publisher = (Animated opening credits) YouTube | accessdate = 2013-10-25 | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/6KeFEUV0U?url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLJZyIXu2hA | archivedate = October 26, 2013 | url-status = live }} NOTE: The title is rendered inaccurately as \"The Marvel Superheroes\" at [http://imdb.com/title/tt0122826/ its entry] on [[IMDb]] and at [http://www.tv.com/the-marvel-superheroes/show/29637/summary.html TV.com].</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[animated television series]] starring five [[comic book]] [[superhero]]es from [[Marvel Comics]]. The first TV series based on Marvel characters, it debuted in [[broadcast syndication|syndication]] on [[United States|U.S.]] television in 1966.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=379}}</ref>\n\nProduced by [[Grantray-Lawrence Animation]], headed by Grant Simmons, Ray Patterson and Robert Lawrence,<ref>Robert Lawrence interview, ''[[Jack Kirby Collector]]'' #41, Fall 2004, pp. 42-47.</ref> it was an umbrella series of five segments, each approximately seven minutes long, broadcast on local [[television stations]] that aired the show at different times. <!--note: few were actually independent stations, as some have written; most were network affiliates, as can be clicked through and seen in the list that appears below in this article--> The series ran initially as a half-hour program made up of three seven-minute segments of a single superhero, separated by a short description of one of the other four heroes. It has also been broadcast as a mixture of various heroes in a half-hour timeslot, and as individual segments as filler or within a [[children's TV program]].<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981, Part 1: Animated Cartoon Series |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/176/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=177-179}}</ref>\n\nThe segments were: \"[[Captain America]]\", \"[[Hulk|The Incredible Hulk]]\", \"[[Iron Man]]\", \"[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|The Mighty Thor]]\" (1962), and \"[[Namor|The Sub-Mariner]]\".\n\n==Production==\nSixty-five half-hour episodes of three seven-minute chapters were produced, for a total of 195 segments that ran initially in broadcast syndication from September 1, 1966 to December 1, 1966.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.tv.com/the-marvel-superheroes/show/29637/episode_listings.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=tabssh&tag=tabs;episodes |title='&#39;The Marvel Superheroes'&#39; Episode Guide |publisher=[[TV.com]] |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last = Thomas|first = Roy|authorlink = Roy Thomas|author2=Sanderson, Peter |authorlink2=Peter Sanderson |title = The Marvel Vault: A Museum-in-a-Book with Rare Collectibles from the World of Marvel|publisher = [[Running Press]]|year = 2007|page = 101|isbn = 978-0762428441|quote= In 1966, television production company Grantray-Lawrence produced a series of five half-hour semi-animated shows under the banner title ''Marvel Superheroes''.<!-- spelling as in cited source --> ''Captain America'' (original comics appearance in 1941), ''The Incredible Hulk'' (1962), ''Iron Man'' (1963), ''The Mighty Thor'', and ''Sub-Mariner'' (1939) all made their television debuts.}}</ref>\n\nThe series, produced in color, had extremely [[limited animation]] produced by [[xerography]], consisting of photocopied images taken directly from the comics and manipulated to minimize the need for animation production. The cartoons were presented as a series of static comic-strip panel images; generally the only movement involved the lips when a character spoke, the eyes, and the occasional arm or leg, or a fully animated black silhouette. The series used the original stories largely in their entirety, showcasing [[Jack Kirby]], [[Steve Ditko]] and [[Don Heck]] art, among others, from the period fans and historians call the [[Silver Age of comic books]].\n\n[[Stan Lee]], Marvel's editor and art director at the time, said in 2004 that he believed publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]] negotiated the deal with Grantray-Lawrence and that Lawrence chose the characters to be used. Lawrence rented Lee and his wife a [[penthouse apartment]] at 30 East 60th Street, near [[Madison Avenue]], for Lee's use while he worked on the series. (Lee lived in [[Hewlett Harbor, New York|Hewlett Harbor]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on [[Long Island]], at the time.) Lee recalled, \"I really don't remember any reaction from the Marvel artists involved. I wish I could claim to have written the [theme song] lyrics, because I think they're brilliant, but alas, I didn't\".<ref>{{Cite journal|title=A Minute of Stan's Time|publisher= (sidebar, Jack Kirby Collector |issue=41 |date=Fall 2004|page= 47|first=Adam |last=McGovern}}</ref> The songs were written by [[Jacques Urbont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmusicsociety.org/news_events/features/2015/071415.html?isArchive=071415|title=The Marvel Super Heroes Songs: The Inside Story|publisher=The Film Music Society|author=Jon Burlingame|date=2015-07-14|accessdate=2018-11-18}}</ref> In the meantime, Grantray-Lawrence subcontracted production of ''The Mighty Thor'' segments to [[Famous Studios|Paramount Cartoon Studios]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} (the animation division of [[Paramount Pictures]], formerly known as Famous Studios), headed at that time by [[Fleischer Studios]] veteran [[Shamus Culhane]].\n\nMarvel announced the series in the \"Marvel Bullpen Bulletins\" of the November 1966 issues, stating in that monthly fan page's hyperbolic style that, \"It won't be long before our swingin' super-heroes <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[sic]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> make their star-studded debut on TV, appearing five nights a week &mdash; that's right, five &mdash; count 'em &mdash; five nights a week, for a half-hour each night. So you've just got time to make sure your set's in good working order &mdash; check your local paper for time and station &mdash; and prepare to have a ball!\"<ref>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins: \"Sensational Secrets and Incredible Inside Information Guilelessly Guaranteed to Avail You Naught!\", in ''[[Tales of Suspense]]'' #83 (Nov. 1966) and other Marvel comics that month.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{expand list|date=November 2014}}\n* [[Carl Banas]] - [[Bucky Barnes]], [[Super-Adaptoid]] \n* [[Sandy Becker]] - [[Captain America|Steve Rogers / Captain America]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tvparty.com/lostny2marvel.html | title= New York City Kid Show Roundup: Marvel Superheroes [sic] | first=Kevin S. |last= Butler | date= n.d. | publisher=TVParty.com | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20010904184549/http://www.tvparty.com/lostny2marvel.html | archivedate= September 4, 2001|url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[Bernard Cowan]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Narrator, [[Odin (character)|Odin]], [[Melter]], Captain Torak, Morgan, [[Ringmaster (comics)|Ringmaster]], Sando/Colonel Von Kraz, \n* [[Jack Creley]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Jack Frost/Professor Shapanka\n* [[Len Carlson]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], [[Loki (comics)|Loki]], [[Mad Thinker]], [[Black Knight (Nathan Garrett)|Nathan Garrett / Black Knight]], President\n* Vern Chapman - [[Edwin Jarvis]], [[Super-Adaptoid]]\n* Henry Comor - [[Gargantus]]\n* Gillie Fenwick - [[Heinrich Zemo|Baron Heinrich Zemo]], [[Radioactive Man (comics)|Radioactive Man]], [[Leader (comics)|Leader]], [[Batroc the Leaper]], [[Space Phantom]], Dr. Cedric Rawlings, [[Heimdall (comics)|Heimdall]], [[Mister Hyde (comics)|Mister Hyde]], Sandu, Premiere Pouldu\n* [[Max Ferguson]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Hulk]]<ref>''Weekend Magazine'' (May 24, 1969)</ref>\n* [[Margaret Griffin]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> - [[Pepper Potts]], [[Black Widow (Natasha Romanova)|Black Widow]], Countess de la Spirosa\n* [[Tom Harvey]] - [[Happy Hogan (comics)|Happy Hogan]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Hank Pym|Giant-Man]], [[Iceman (Marvel Comics)|Iceman]], [[Chameleon (Marvel Comics)|Chameleon]], [[Super-Skrull]], [[Crimson Dynamo|Anton Vanko / Crimson Dynamo]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> Borok\n* [[Paul Kligman]] - [[Thunderbolt Ross]], [[Red Skull]], [[Krang (Marvel Comics)|Warlord Krang]], [[Mole Man]], [[Metal Master (comics)|Metal Master]], [[Erik Josten|Power Man]]\n* Vita Linder<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Betty Ross]], [[Dorma (comics)|Lady Dorma]], [[Jane Foster (comics)|Jane Foster]], [[Enchantress (Marvel Comics)|Enchantress]], [[Scarlet Witch]],  [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]], [[Sharon Carter]], [[Peggy Carter]], [[Lorelei (Asgardian)|Lorelei]], Celia Rawlings, Hippolyta\n* [[Don Mason (actor)|Don Mason]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref>\n* Douglas Master - Senator Harrington Boyd<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n* [[Ed McNamara]] - [[Swordsman (comics)|Swordsman]], [[Titanium Man]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Boomerang (comics)|Boomerang]], [[Mad Thinker]]\n* Claude Rae<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref>\n* Henry Ramer<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - Major Uberhart, [[Doctor Doom]], Wolfgang, Vashti, [[Mandarin (comics)|Mandarin]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n* [[Paul Soles]] - [[Hulk|Bruce Banner]], [[Attuma]], [[Rick Jones (comics)|Rick Jones]]\n* [[John Vernon]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Iron Man|Iron Man/Tony Stark]],<ref>http://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/iron-man-the-first-and-cheapest</ref> [[Namor|Sub-Mariner/Prince Namor]],<ref>http://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/iron-man-the-first-and-cheapest</ref> Major [[Glenn Talbot]], Major Corey\n* [[Chris Wiggins]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ivrygiir_Lo</ref> - [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor/Dr. Donald Blake]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chriswigginsonline.8k.com/films.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224021156/http://chriswigginsonline.8k.com/films.html |archivedate=2015-02-24 }}</ref> [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Kraven the Hunter|Kraven]],<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref> [[Grey Gargoyle]], Byrrah, [[Balder (comics)|Balder]], [[Blizzard (comics)|Jack Frost]], Molto, [[Professor X]], [[Count Nefaria]]<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>\n\nFor [[WNAC-TV]] in Boston, Arthur Pierce portrayed Captain America in live-action segments for the show. Actors portraying other characters, including Dr. Doom, Hulk, and Bucky, also appeared in live-action segments. The segments were scripted by Superman co-creator [[Jerry Siegel]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Age of TV Heroes: The Live-Action Adventures of Your Favorite Comic Book Characters |last=Hofius |first=Jason |authorlink= |author2=George Khoury   | year = 2010 | publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |location= |isbn=1-60549-010-5}}</ref>\n\n==Guest characters==\nAppearing in guest roles were:\n* [[X-Men|The X-Men]] &mdash; The original lineup of the [[Warren Worthington|Angel]], the [[Beast (comics)|Beast]], [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]], [[Iceman (comics)|Iceman]], and [[Jean Grey|Marvel Girl]] appeared in a Sub-Mariner episode, \"Dr. Doom's Day / The Doomed Allegiance / Tug of Death\". The story was an adaptation of ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #6 (Sept. 1962), but since Grantray-Lawrence Animation did not own rights to the [[Fantastic Four (1967 animated series)|Fantastic Four]], the producers substituted the X-Men &mdash; although referring to them instead as \"Allies for Peace\". However, the characters retained their original designs and individual names from the comics.\n* [[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]] &mdash; Episode 8 of The Incredible Hulk was an adaptation of ''Avengers'' #2 (Nov. 1963), and co-starred Thor, Iron Man (with his early golden armor recolored to match the red-and-gold design featured in the Iron Man episodes), [[Giant-Man]], the [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]]. The lineup beginning in ''Avengers'' #4 (March 1964), with Thor, Iron Man, Giant-Man, the Wasp and the newly installed Captain America, appears in several ''Captain America'' episodes, as does the later line-up from Avengers #16 with [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]], [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], and the [[Scarlet Witch]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2010}}\nEach episode consisted of three chapters.\n\n===''Captain America''===\n[[File:MSH-CaptainAmerica 1966TVtoon.jpg|thumb|250px|A [[Captain America]] title card]]\n*Episode 1: The Origin of [[Captain America]], Wreckers Among Us, Enter [[Red Skull]]\n*Episode 2: The Sentinel and the Spy, The Fantastic Origin of the Red Skull, Lest Tyranny Triumph\n*Episode 3: Midnight in Greymoor Castle, If This Be Treason, When You Lie Down With Dogs\n*Episode 4: Return of Captain America, The Search, To Live Again\n*Episode 5: [[Baron Zemo|Zemo]] and the [[Masters of Evil]], Zemo Strikes, The Fury of Zemo\n*Episode 6: The Revenge of Captain America, The Trap Is Sprung, So Dies A Villain\n*Episode 7: Let The Past Be Gone, The [[Super-Adaptoid|Adaptoid]], The [[Super-Adaptoid|Super Adaptoid]]\n*Episode 8: Coming of the [[Swordsman (comics)#Jacques Duquesne|Swordsman]], Vengeance Is Ours, Emissary of Destruction\n*Episode 9: Bitter Taste of Defeat, Sorcery Triumph, The Road Back\n*Episode 10: Doorway to Doom, When the Commissar Commands, Duel Or Die\n*Episode 11: The [[Sleeper (Marvel Comics)|Sleeper]] Shall Awake, Where Walks the Sleeper, The Final Sleep\n*Episode 12: The Girl from Cap's Past, The Stage Is Set, 30 Minutes to Live\n*Episode 13: The Red Skull Lives, He Who Holds the [[Cosmic Cube]], The Red Skull Supreme\n\n===''The Incredible Hulk''===\n[[File:Hulk Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|250px|One depiction of the [[Hulk]] in ''The Marvel Super Heroes'']]\n*Episode 1: The Origin of the [[Hulk]], Enter the Gorgon, To Be a Man\n*Episode 2: Terror of the Toadmen, Bruce Banner: Wanted For Treason, Hulk Runs Amok\n*Episode 3: A Titan Rides the Train, The Horde of Humanoids, On the Rampage!\n*Episode 4: The Power of Dr. Banner, Where Strides the Behemoth, Back from the Dead\n*Episode 5: Micro Monsters, The Lair of the [[Leader (comics)|Leader]], To Live Again\n*Episode 6: Brawn Against Brain, Captured At Last, Enter the [[Chameleon (comics)|Chameleon]]\n*Episode 7: Within this Monster Dwells a Man; Another World, Another Foe; The Wisdom of the [[Uatu|Watcher]]\n*Episode 8: The [[Space Phantom]], Sting of the Wasp, Exit the Hulk\n*Episode 9: Hulk vs. Metal Master, The Master Tests His Metal, Mind Over Metal\n*Episode 10: The [[Ringmaster (comics)|Ringmaster]], Captive of the [[Circus of Crime|Circus]], The Grand Finale\n*Episode 11: Enter [[Tyrannus (comics)|Tyrannus]], Beauty & The Beast, They Dwell in the Depths\n*Episode 12: Terror of the T-Gun, I Against A World, Bruce Banner is the Hulk\n*Episode 13: The Man Called Boomerang; Hulk Intervenes; Less Than Monster, More Than Man\n\n===''The Invincible Iron Man<ref>The Marvel Super Heroes on TV! Book One: Iron Man (2017) - by J. Ballmann, ISBN 9 781545 345658</ref>''===\n[[File:Iron Man Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|250px|One depiction of [[Iron Man]] in the series]]\n*Episode 1: Double Disaster, Enter [[Happy Hogan (comics)|Happy Hogan]], Of Ice and Men\n*Episode 2: The Death of [[Tony Stark]]!, The Hands of the [[Mandarin (comics)|Mandarin]], The Origin of The Mandarin\n*Episode 3: [[Ultimo (Marvel Comics)|Ultimo]], Ultimo Lives, Crescendo\n*Episode 4: The Mandarin's Revenge!, The Mandarin's Death Ray, No One Escapes the Mandarin\n*Episode 5: [[Crimson Dynamo]]!, The Crimson Dynamo Strikes, Captured\n*Episode 6: Enter [[Clint Barton|Hawkeye]], So Spins the Web, Triple Jeopardy\n*Episode 7: If I Die, Let It Be With Honor; Fight On, For A World Is Watching; What Price Victory?\n*Episode 8: The [[Mole Man (comics)|Moleman]] Strikes, The Dragon of the Flames, Decision Under the Earth\n*Episode 9: The Other [[Iron Man]]!, Death Duel, Into The Jaws of the Death\n*Episode 10: The Cliffs of Doom!, The False Captain America, The Unmasking\n*Episode 11: My Life For Yours, The [[Nathan Garrett|Black Knight]]'s Gambit, The Menace of the Monster\n*Episode 12: The Dream Master, If A Man Be Mad, Duel In Space\n*Episode 13: Beauty and the Armor, Peril in Space, As A City Watches\n\n===''The Mighty Thor''===\n[[File:Thor Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] title card]]\n*Episode 1: Trapped by [[Loki (Marvel Comics)|Loki]], The Vengeance of Loki, The Defeat of Loki\n*Episode 2: Chained Evil; Sandu, Master of the Supernatural; Enchanted Hammer\n*Episode 3: [[Enchantress (comics)|Enchantress]] and [[Executioner (comics)|Executioner]], Giants Walk the Earth, Battle of the Gods\n*Episode 4: At the Mercy of Loki, Trial of the Gods, Return To Earth\n*Episode 5: The [[Absorbing Man]]; In My Hands, This Hammer; Vengeance of the Thunder God\n*Episode 6: To Kill A Thunder God, The Day of the [[Destroyer (Thor)|Destroyer]], Terror of the Tomb\n*Episode 7: The [[Grey Gargoyle]], The Wrath of [[Odin (Marvel Comics)|Odin]], Triumph in Stone