the Web. Wikipedia disallows forum postings or blogs, or commercial sales site.\nSegments of the series were released on [[VHS]] in 1985 from Prism Entertainment as part of the \"Marvel Comics Video Library\" series. In the early 1990s, other segments of the series, as well as some other Marvel Comics based animated series, were re-released on VHS, with distribution by Best Film & Video Corp. under the '''Marvel Video!''' banner from 1991-1994.-->\nSegments of the series appear on at least two [[VHS]] [[home video]] releases, containing three [[videocassettes]] each: ''Marvel Superheroes: Triple Pack #1'' ([[Universal Product Code|UPC]] #024543004127) and ''Marvel's Mightiest Heroes: Triple Pack #2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/marvels_mightiest_heroes_triple_pack_2/ |title='Marvel's Mightiest Heroes: Triple Pack #2' |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|Fox Video]] released a version titled ''Marvel's Mightiest Super Heroes Gift Set'' ([[European Article Number|EAN]] #0024543004134).\n\nIn 2003, Hulk segments giving his [[origin story]] appeared as an extra on the [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] DVD release of the 1996 [[animated television series]] ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1996 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/read.php?ID=6664 |title='The Incredible Hulk' (Animated Series) |first=James W. |last=Powell |publisher=(review) DVDTalk.com |date=June 17, 2003|accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] announced plans to release ''The Marvel Superheroes Show'' on June 28, 2005, as a five-DVD set titled ''The 60's Superheroes''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2176 |title=The Marvel Superheroes - Capt. America! Hulk! Thor! Iron Man! Sub-Mariner! |first=David |last=Lambert |publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com |date=September 24, 2004 |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060208224211/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2176 |archivedate=February 8, 2006 }}</ref> By February 2005, however, the release was off the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2838|title=The Marvel Superheroes - Studio Says 'Superheroes' are Off the Schedule|first=David|last=Lambert|publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com|date=February 1, 2005|accessdate=2011-01-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818030710/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/newsitem.cfm?NewsID=2838|archivedate=August 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2007, the [[United Kingdom|UK]] company Maximum Entertainment released four two-disc sets, for [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 2]], each set containing 13 episodes of the Captain America, Iron Man, Sub-Mariner and Thor segments respectively, with each episode re-edited into continuous, half-hour segments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.toonzone.net/article.php?ID=18200|date=July 23, 2007|title='The Marvel Super Heroes': Classic Comics in Suspended Animation|author=\"Jon T\" (pseudonym)|publisher=Toon Zone|accessdate=2011-01-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211034951/http://news.toonzone.net/article.php?ID=18200|archivedate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> On August 25, 2008, the UK  company Liberation Entertainment released a two-disc set of the Hulk segments, re-edited into 13 20-minute episodes.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Canada|Cartoon|Speculative fiction|1960s}}\n* {{imdb title|206513|The Sub-Mariner}}\n* {{imdb title|0206474|Captain America}}\n* {{imdb title|0206488|The Incredible Hulk}}\n* {{imdb title|0206490|Iron Man}}\n* {{imdb title|0156221|The Mighty Thor}}\n* {{bcdb |Other_Studios/G/Grantray-Lawrence_Animation/The_